in the context of political, cultural, and ideological trends, noting the paradoxes inherent in the attempt to provide essential services and reflect at the same time the intentions of the state. He concludes by examining the turning point faced by the social work profession in the 1980s, indicated by a return to casework and a withdrawal from social policy concerns.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSocial servicezUnited StatesxHistory. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSocial Work. 4aU.S. History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh  asocietal trends, social reform and social work, social control, sociological analysis, ideological trends, political science and sociology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147123040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801471230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801471230/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles